  <title>Post: What is build-essentials for openSUSE</title>
  <link>https://randomgeekery.org/post/2014/06/what-is-build-essentials-for-opensuse/</link>
  <pubDate>Sun, 22 Jun 2014 00:00:00 -0700</pubDate>
  
  <guid>https://randomgeekery.org/post/2014/06/what-is-build-essentials-for-opensuse/</guid>
  <description>&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[!NOTE] &lt;a href=&#34;https://randomgeekery.org/card/tldr/&#34;&gt;tldr&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;code&gt;devel_basis&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;</description>
   <category>post</category> 
   <category>post</category> 
   <category>suse</category>  <category>tools</category> 
  <content:encoded><![CDATA[<blockquote>
<p>[!NOTE] <a href="/card/tldr/">tldr</a>
<code>devel_basis</code></p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is the umpteenth time I looked up what <a href="http://packages.ubuntu.com/trusty/build-essential">build-essential</a> is on <a href="http://opensuse.org">openSUSE</a>.
For my purposes, it&rsquo;s the <a href="http://software.opensuse.org/package/patterns-openSUSE-devel_basis">devel_basis</a> pattern.</p>
<p>To see what packages have the pattern,</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"><code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh"><span class="line"><span class="cl">zypper info -t pattern devel_basis
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Yes it has a lot of packages, but I usually end up installing many of those anyways.</p>
<p>To install <code>devel_basis</code>,</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"><code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh"><span class="line"><span class="cl">sudo zypper install -t pattern devel_basis
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>That&rsquo;s all. I&rsquo;ve started remembering to <em>use</em> the notes on my site, which  means it occurs to me that more notes would be helpful.</p>]]></content:encoded>
